<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1922-01-27T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1922-01-27T05:00:00-05:00" n="788" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d788">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/1267: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-01-27T18:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">January 27,
                                        1922—6 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received 6:45
                            p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>31. Have just seen Yen. He tells me he telegraphed last night to Chinese
                            delegation the instructions described in my number 28, January 26th, 12
                            midnight [<hi rend="italic">noon?</hi>].</p>
                        <p>Shantung settlement seems therefore assured. I sincerely congratulate
                            President, Secretary and other members delegation.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Schurman</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>